3. Fetch data using AJAX and display asynchronously
Fetch Data using AJAX (with JavaScript)
Here‚Äôs a simple demo that fetches data from a text file (data.txt) and displays it:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>AJAX Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h2>Fetch Data using AJAX</h2>

  <button onclick="loadData()">Fetch Data</button>
  <p id="output"></p>

  <script>
    function loadData() {
      // Create XMLHttpRequest object
      let xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();

      // Open request: GET request to "data.txt"
      xhr.open("GET", "data.txt", true);

      // When request completes
      xhr.onload = function() {
        if (xhr.status == 200) {
          document.getElementById("output").innerHTML = xhr.responseText;
        } else {
          document.getElementById("output").innerHTML = "Error loading data.";
        }
      };

      // Send the request
      xhr.send();
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>

Procedure:
Step 1: Prepare the files
Create a project folder (example: AJAXDemo) and put the following two files inside it:
1.	index.html ‚Üí your HTML program (the above code)
2.	data.txt ‚Üí a simple text file with some content (for example:

 Hello, this text was loaded using AJAX!
Using VS Code (Live Server extension)
1.	Install Visual Studio Code.

2.	Open your project folder in VS Code.

3.	Install the extension Live Server.

4.	Right-click index.html ‚Üí Open with Live Server.

5.	The browser will open with http://127.0.0.1:5500/index.html (or similar).
Step 1: Open VS Code
‚óè	Launch Visual Studio Code.

‚óè	Open your project folder (e.g., AJAXDemo where you have index.html and data.txt).

________________________________________
üîπ Step 2: Install Live Server Extension
1.	Look at the left sidebar in VS Code and click the Extensions icon (it looks like 4 small squares).
 (Shortcut: press Ctrl+Shift+X on Windows/Linux or Cmd+Shift+X on Mac)

In the search bar, type:

 Live Server
2.	
3.	Find the extension by Ritwick Dey (most popular one).

4.	Click Install.

Step 3: Run with Live Server
1.	Once installed, open your index.html file in VS Code.

2.	Right-click anywhere inside the file and select:
 üëâ ‚ÄúOpen with Live Server‚Äù

3.	A browser window will open at an address like:

 http://127.0.0.1:5500/index.html
Step 4: Test
‚óè	Click your Fetch Data button.

‚óè	If data.txt is in the same folder, you‚Äôll see its content displayed inside the page
